citeinfo.title: BLM REA NOS 2012 Caribou Subsistence Use Areas in the North Slope

descript.abstract: Subsistence practices are closely linked to the natural cycles of the environment. Such practices include hunting, fishing, and gathering of various animal and plant species in the region. The majority of the population in remote rural Alaska depends substantially on subsistence to supplement their wages. Fishing and hunting are essential parts of local livelihoods in the North Slope study area. Subsistence forms a substantial part of the household and community economy in the region. Subsistence foods are a large part of household food consumption. According to the Survey of Living Conditions in the Arctic, subsistence foods make up between half and three-quarters of all food consumed by Alaska Native households. Even though only 30% of the populations reports hunting, nearly everyone reports using subsistence foods, illustrating widespread sharing and the significance of the role hunters have as part of a communityâ€™s holistic system. Subsistence traditions connect people to each other, the animals, and land they have used for thousands of years. This is especially true of Alaska Natives, who are among the very few aboriginal groups in the world that have not been displaced from their traditional lands.
descript.purpose: This dataset shows subsistence use areas for 8 communities of Alaska's North Slope - Wainwright, Barrow, Anaktuvuk Pass, Atqasuk, Barter Island, Nuiqsut, Point Hope and Point Lay. The subsistence resources/activities are: FISHING, MOOSE, CARIBOU, WILDFOWL, FURBEARERS, VEGETATION.
descript.supplinf: Note: resource use areas change through time and are not fixed entities. Land outside these areas should not be assumed to be less important to community residents.

attracc.attraccr: The following information about the data quality was received along with the data from the North Slope Borough: 1) The areas are approximate, and should be used only to show general use areas. Some of the data is also out of date. 2) There are some minor flaws in the coding of some polygons. There is little documentation about the coverages, so we are trying to reconstruct as much as we can. In the meantime, the data appear to ba accurate enough for use as approximations of subsistence use areas. 3) The data were collected from interviews with selected hunters in each village. The resolution is imprecise, and Sverre Pedersen has reservations about the accuracy, especially for some villages.

procstep.procdesc: Coverages repdefined from Alaska Albers Clarke1866 to Alaska AlbersNAD27. Further reprojected to Alaska Albers NAD83 using the "NAD_1927_To_NAD_1983_Alaska" geographic transformation. Coverages migrated into shapefiles and geodatabases as file formats have changed over time. For cartographic display in planning efforts and projects, files have been split into individual resources and communities to allow for displaying overlapping areas.

procstep.procdesc: NSB automated the data from Pedersen, S., 1979. Regional subsistence land use, North Slope Borough, Alaska.
polygons from each community were combined using the Union tool in ArcGIS based on the species attribute and exported to new feature classes for each species.
